As Wright’s Law drives TSLA costs down, I believe that we will see a measured decline in TSLA vehicle pricing, while they maintain strong margins. The decline will NOT be to keep pace with the EV competition, but to drive adoption growth, as TSLA competition is ICE, not EVs.

TSLA innovations – battery/software/autonomy/drivetrain/structural adaptations/manufacturing evolutions/infrastructure build/business model – drives a flywheel of continually improving margins. Wright’s Law provides a construct by which to measure and predict the impacts.

There are a very large number of confounders here as there are so many impacts on GP. However, in simple terms, TSLA achieved, in 2021, a gross margin of 26.5% in Q1 and 29% in Q2. These results are slightly short of Sam’s targets, but – in my book – uncannily close.

Wright’s Law “states that for every cumulative doubling of units produced, costs will fall by a constant percentage.” In September 2019 Sam predicted that TSLA GP would rise from the then 17.2% to more than 30% by the end of 2020 (at constant Average Selling Prices – ASPs).

So now to Wright’s Law. This is a little complicated. @skorusARK first propounded the view that TSLA is subject to this interesting dynamic. My view is that the secular rise in TSLA gross margin since inception is an indicator of the efficacy of the theory https://t.co/qlj5xJnSPx

Following their stumble with initiating production of the M3 in 2017, TSLA have shown outstanding execution, with little downward pressure on margins from the introduction of MY in Fremont, M3 and MY in Shanghai. My hope is that things will go equally smoothly in 2022.

Given that I anticipate earnings of over $8 per share from TSLA current operations in 2022 from sales of under $60b, my expectations are that Berlin and Austin will add over 60% additional earnings for about 40% increase in revenues

I want to be clear. I do not respect the Guardian. I do not respect it.

물론 팔란티어도 좋아보이는 회사지만, 
그걸 아직 못찾아서 투자를 못하고 있다.

높은 PER의 정당화를 위해서는 
그에 걸맞는 분기 실적 성장이 꼭 필요하다.

그런면에서 테슬라의 2020.4Q의 어닝미스는 
좀 뼈아픈 부분이었다. 
(비트코인, 도지 등 다른 이유도 있었지만)

테슬라 Fwd p/e = 102
팔란티어 Fwd p/e = 123

팔란티어에 투자를 하려면 
팔란티어가 테슬라 이상의 
EPS성장을 보일것이다 라는 무언가가 있어야 한다. 
그래야 배수를 더 쳐줄수 있으니까.

밸류에이션에 대한 개인적인 생각

제일 쉽게 말해서 
주가 = EPS(실적) * PER (배수)다.

성장주에게 과거실적을 바탕으로 하는 PER은 
별 의미 없다고 볼수 있지만, 
향후 실적을 바탕으로 하는 PER은 좀 의미가 있다.
